      "cover": "scooter_cover.png",
      "description": "This is a custom electric scooter built to be as compact as possible while still being usable for short to medium distance commutes. It was built over around 7 months from sketchbook to test rides with a budget of $1k.%%The scooter undergoing trials in Feburary,20250218_170548.jpg%%There seems to be an plague of electric scooters sweeping across university campuses lately, or at least that's the case at Stony Brook. Seeing this, I decided to join in and use a scooter for my mobility needs. More specifically, I needed a way to get from where I was living to campus about 2.5 miles away and it was ideally very portable and fast. Commericial products seemed to only ever check two out of three of those boxes, so I decided to design one to check all the boxes.%%The CAD of the scooter,scooterDesign.png%% The design of the scooter heavily borrows from my combat robot experience, being aluminum sheet metal joined with nutstrips so I can order the parts from <a href=\"https://sendcutsend.com/\">SendCutSend</a> for relatively cheap. The most ambitious design element is the folding deck which was required to minimize the size of the scooter when folded. The stem of the scooter also folds down into thirds and then folds down onto the deck. %%b%%With the main design finalized, I calculated my final cost to be about $995, ever so slightly below budget. %%Specifications,h%% Before committing to the design, I did a lot of market research into existing compact scooter designs. Now that I am writing this in retrospect, I can compare the data gathered from test runs against the specifications of those other scooters.%%b%% A good portion of the designs, especially those at the smallest end of folded volume, were either early or limited crowdfunding campaigns or discontinued products. Shown below are the physical specifications of my scooter compared with 10 other scooters. The raw data and sources can be found <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1f_MRLitBwHNer3pAdbpCN1bQak1OpVClRnMCl3yneUM/edit?usp=sharing\">here</a>.%%b%%<br/> %%A comparison of volume and weight of my scooter against other similar products,techSpecs.png%% Although the folded volume is not a great measure of compactness as a longer scooter will have the same volume as a shorter but taller scooter even when the shorter scooter may be more compact in typical use. However, it still provides a reasonable estimate of the size of my scooter.%%b%% The performance in terms of range and top speed can also be compared, although the max speed is a conservative estimate based on the new battery upgrade and the 40kph obtained with the current battery setup. %%b%%<br/>%%A comparison of range and top speed of my scooter against other similar products,perfSpecs.png%% The range is superior or the same as all the listed scooters except the non-midfolding scooters. Meanwhile the speed is superior to all similar scooters. Note that the top speed was not achieved during the same trial as the range trial. %%Stem highlighted on the CAD,stemMountStem.png%% Starting with the stem and stem holder, shown in blue and turqoiuse respectively, this was the component which needed the most prototyping. My initial design for the upper portion of the stem was quite different from the final iteration. I was worried that a tube-based stem would be too finicky to fold and wouldn't save enough room. Thus, I came up with a alternate design using an aluminum L extrusions and sheet metal which can collapse outwards.%%20241214-2202-42.3956893.mp4%% This design did turn out to be extremely compact and easy to use, however it was about as rigid as a wet noodle when it came to actually twisting the handle to steer. I went back to the drawing board and came up with the current design which would fold into thirds and just barely left enough room for the stem fold down. This design actually turned out to be even more compact with a greater unfolded height as well.%%Old and new stem design,stemDesign.png%%With the design finalized, I started with machining the series of aluminum tubes. The large tube which the stem sits inside was sawed down to size and cleaned up on my lathe, then inserted into two CNC spindle holders. %%The stem tube being machined,stem.png%%The stem itself was harder to make as I didn't have a 4 axis mill to drill the holes in the tube. Instead, I used the next best thing, a 3D-printed jig with a drill guide which perfectly sits on top of the jig.%%The stem being drilled and the drill jig,drillJig.png%% With this new design, I quickly discovered the hook on the latch was not strong enough and would bend when I accelerated too quickly. To fix this, I would need to make a hook made without sheet metal bending, which was outside of my capabilities. Fortunately, my friend happened to be working on his own CNC mill, so I sent the part over and waited. %%A comaprison of the old and new hook,hook.png%%The carry handle was created by hand once the rest of the stem was assembled. The brackets were cut out from an old steel combat robot top plate and the rest of the handle was modeled and printed afterwards.%%The brackets and handle,carryHandle.png%% %%Deck highlighted on the CAD,deck.png%%The deck is the core of this design as it was the limiting factor in how small I could make it. Looking around at commericial or even weird one-off designs that never made it to production, I decided to attempt a feature which as far as I can tell, only a small handful of scooters have attempted: a folding deck. My solution was the simpliest implementation, spliting the deck right down the middle. This way I could take advantage of having identical front and rear panels and save some money through the SendCutSend volume discount. Two hinges and two latches would attach the two deck halves together and I made sure every component in this critical assembly would be able to hold up to the forces with a very large margin of safety. In order to save some weight without impacting performance, the frame rails were topology optimized using Inventor's built-in shape generator. %%b%%As the pieces of the deck were already cut and bent by SendCutSend, all I had to do was put the pieces together. I used #10-24 screws with <a href=\"https://www.fingertechrobotics.com/proddetail.php?prod=ft-nutstrip\">nutstrips</a> to join the panels at 90 degree angles.%%Putting the two segments of the deck together,deckAssemble.png%% %%Drive pod highlighted on the CAD,drivePod.png%% The drive pod was the most complex component to put together due to the many fast moving parts. The sprockets for the chain reduction were cut by SendCutSend too, but needed bevels added to the teeth. This was done by attaching them to a hand drill and spinning the sprockets against a belt sander. The chain drive could then be fully assembled. %%20250105_200744.mp4%% A plastic spacer was then pressed onto the rear wheel allowing nine 1/4\" bolts to attach the large sprocket to the wheel. The smaller sprocket was then attached to the motor using four high-load M3 screws and another 3D-printed spacer with a stepped aluminum shaft I made on my lathe. The motor could then be bolted to the aluminum panels and the wheel mounted on a 8mm shaft. %%The wheel being mounted to the drive pod,drivePodAssem.png%% %%Electronics highlighted on the CAD,electronicsBanner.png%%The electrical system of the scooter is only comprised of three main components, the battery, the switch, and the speed controller. For the latter two, I repurposed parts not typically meant for an electric land vehicle. The switch was intended as a battery disconnect for a boat, and thus was well suited for the high current loads the motor was drawing. The speed controller was a large 150 Amp ESC meant for airplanes, thus extremely compact for the power output. %%Main switch and full electrical system,electronics.png%% These components would take up the majority of the space inside the deck of the scooter. The battery lives inside a large compliant TPU sleeve inside the forward half of the deck. The sleeve was the largest TPU print I had ever done, measuring almost a foot long. The switch and the speed controller lives in the other half of the deck in custom enclosures designed to mount to the nutstrips inside the frame. A cable sleeve connected the two halves such that the scooter could fold and unfold without damaging the wiring.%%The three aforementioned housings for the electrical components,electronicsComponents.png%% In addition to the major components, a couple peripherals would allow me to control the scooter. An Arduino Nano powered by a BEC would interpret the signal from a throttle mounted on the handlebars and feed that to the speed controller. This would also let me later do throttle smoothing and potentially implement other smart features like having current and voltage feedback. This all fits into a small box sitting next to the main switch.%%The box which holds the Arduino,arduinoEnclosure.png%% For the throttle, I originally tried to design my own using a 3D-printed TPU spring inside something that was supposed to resemble a ship's helm. This showed early promise and I learned a lot about designing 3D-printed springs. However the final product would sometimes get stuck which would be dangerous, and the design was dropped for an off-the-shelf throttle for a different scooter.%%%% This would still involve some challenges, mainly shutting off the throttle whenever the brake was pressed. I solved this with an old spare limit switch from a 3D-printer. This was set up such that the throttle would only send a signal if the limit switch was pressed, which would only be when the brake was not engaged. %%The brake limit switch mounted on the brake handle,20250315_011224.jpg%% %%Cooling system highlighted on the CAD,coolingSystem.png%% After a couple simple tests going back and forth, it became apparent that there was a significant thermal issue with the motor. It would get too hot to touch within minutes of high load running. It was too late to consider a different motor, so I devised a cooling system using heat pipes which would transfer heat from a copper plate backing the motor to two large aluminum heatsinks above the drive pod.%%Cooling system highlighted in green,Screenshot 2025-12-28 154700.png%%The copper plate was cut using a hacksaw and a lot of patience with a hand file. A bit of solder was used to reinforce a weak spot via blowtorch. I designed a custom 3D-printed tool to bend the heat pipes without damaging them. The bent pipes then fit into the matching cutouts on the copper plate. %%The copper plate and heat pipes being bent,copperPlate.png%%The heatsink assembly was contructed from two off-the-shelf heatsinks bolted to a larger copper plate with similar cutouts for the ends of the heat pipes. %%The making of the heatsink and integration,heatsink.png%% Thermal paste was used to ensure good thermal contact between every surface and aluminum supports were added to hold the heatsink in place."
