      "title": "Differential Swerve",
      "link": "3",
      "cover": "ds_cover.png",
      "description": "This is a series of experimental swerve drives designed for combat robotics implementing differential swerve and shuffler technology. The ultimate goal would be to mount this on a new robot for NHRL combat robotics.%%b%%<iframe height=\"300\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/moCGVyodcd4\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe> %%A demonstration of forwards drive in CAD,DSS-example.gif%%I wanted to develop a new swerve drive system for combat robotics, something that I feel had not been fully explored yet. With my experience from building a differential swerve drive in 10th grade, I created a new version 2 with updated mechanics. While keeping the omni-directional movement and power of a differential swerve drive, I integrated a walking shuffler mechanism to replace the wheel. The benefit is two-fold: allowing the robot to take advantage of the \"Non-Traditional (wheel-less) Locomotion\" weight bonus offered by NHRL, as well as being able to fit in a much narrower profile compared to a wheel. Both direction and speed of each swerve module is controlled via the turning of two large ring gears. When the two gears rotate in opposite directions, the module moves forwards. When in the same direction, the entire module changes direction with it. Shown below is a demonstration of turning and moving forward using an unassembled drive.%%20240501_213927.mp4%%The shuffler system uses a series of mechanical cams mounted on a center axle to produce an approximation of walking. The version mounted inside the swerve drive was designed to fit a tall and narrow profile, shown below is an early proof-of-concept prototype.%%An early prototype,PXL_20240205_032522712.jpg%%This combination of concepts was (as far as I could find) not something which had been built before. The design of V2 was similar to my first differential-swerve attempt with the 3D-printed construction. However, it is under half of the width and actually outfitted with a full set of electronics. Two 2216 BLDC motors drive the module and a magnetic encoder detects the angle it is currently pointed.%%b%%Originally, I had also planned for a 3D-printed gearbox to serve as the 5:1 ratio the motors needed in order to provide enough torque. While the gearboxes worked, it quickly became apparent that there was a durability issue. First, the modules were melting themselves, so I turned out some brass bearings and tried higher temperature filaments. This extended the time they lasted, but not nearly enough. Not wanting to deal with another potential point of failure, I shelved the custom gearbox for now.%%20240301_203610.mp4%%Making the control code for this project was something completely new to me. I used an Arduino Mega microcontroller for its number of ports. The solution I came to was to set the base speed of the two motors to the throttle value and then use PID to speed up or slow down each individual motor such that the module rotates towards a target angle.%%20240401_223855.mp4%%With a functional design, I manufactured a second module and started working on the frame of a robot I could mount them to. The robot is constructed from plasma-cut mild steel panels held together with nutstrips.%%The second swerve drive and frame,swerveDrives.png%%To replace the 3D-printed gearboxes, I bought some cheap gearboxes which came with their own pinion. However, I needed to reduce the diameter of the motor shaft to press the pinion onto it, and to remove the motor shaft I used a lighter to heat up the casing. Then I used the lathe to turn the shaft down until the pinion could be pressed on and gearbox attached.%%The shaft being removed and then fitted into the gearbox,pinion.png%%To fulfill the active weapon requirement, I designed a waggle stick using a brushed motor with a 130:1 reduction. The stick itself is a piece of bent 1/4\" chromoly from SendCutSend. %%Finished construction of the waggle stick,waggleStick.png%% %%20240617_214011.mp4%% Testing the swerve drive units on the ground produced mixed results. They would work in moving the robot around, but were very unreliable and would only go in the desired direction half the time. %%20240615_221643.mp4%% Unfortunately, there was no time left for this version of the robot, as the NHRL event was only a few days away. This ultimately resulted in the robot not passing safety and not competing due to the unreliable drive. I spent most of the event modifying code and fixing the swerves when they broke during testing. It was also apparent that the design itself was flawed. Fixing the drives took way too much time. Accessing or removing any part of the drive involved taking apart the entire module. The construction was also overall too tall, leading the robot to almost exceed the weight limit. %%b%% When I got back, I started thinking about a complete redesign using the lessons I learned. This V3 design would aim to use the same parts as V2 but be half the size in terms of height, have an assembly that entirely disassembles with a couple screws, and better reliability. Minimizing the size was the greatest challenge. The first innovation was to reorient the motors horizontally and use a stepped bevel gear as the ring gear. This eliminated the limiting factor on the height of the module and also let the motors be directly removable from the frame without disassembling the rest of the assembly.%%The gears of the new design.,Screenshot 2026-01-02 171727.png%%The encoder gear was also repositioned from the top of the module to the center to save a bit of additional space. The 1:1 output gearing for the encoder was kept but instead of the large output gear, a chain of smaller gears achieved the same gearing in a much more compact package. Note how the gear under the green encoder rotates at the same angular speed the module does.%%Screen Recording 2026-01-02 173103.mp4%%Although this design started with shufflers, with this much weight and size savings, I was also able to return to a wheeled robot. I noticed that one of the problems with V2 was the shufflers causing the robot to bounce around which potentially led to something breaking. In order to fit a wheeled system into the tall cylindrical space where the shufflers were, I designed a belted arrangement where a tread would tranfer torque while also being the surface that contacts the ground. %%20241227_115159.mp4%%This change would also help with simplifying the construction. Now without the long shuffler legs in the way, simply removing four M3 bolts which hold the top and bottom halves of the outer shell separates the halves and allows easy access to all the internals. %%Storyboard1.mp4%% The final V3 design is very promising and may finally make its way into a competitive robot. Since the initial build of the first V3 drive unit, this project has taken a backseat to my <a href=\"./projects.html?proj=escooter\">electric scooter project</a>. However, as that project and its upgrades wrap up, I am looking to start development of this diffy swerve once again. %%V1 to V3 of the swerve drive,diffy.png%%"
